<DOC><DOCNO> AP880711-0245 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1924EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Dialog-Knight-Ridder 1stLd-Writethru f0253 07-11 0261</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Dialog-Knight-Ridder, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0253,0268</SECOND><HEAD>Knight-Ridder Acquiring Database Service</HEAD><NOTE>EDs: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with Lockheed comment, other material.</NOTE><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Knight-Ridder Inc. will buy Dialog InformationServices Inc., the world's biggest electronic information retrievalcompany, for $353 million from Lockheed Corp., Knight-Ridderannounced Monday.   Dialog, which had revenue of $98 million last year, has morethan 91,000 subscribers in 86 countries, and collects informationfrom more than 320 databases.   ``The acquisition of Dialog represents a significant increase inKnight-Ridder's commitment to electronic information services anddoubles the size of our rapidly expanding business informationservices division,'' said James K. Batten, president and chiefexecutive officer of Knight-Ridder.   David K. Ray, president of the company's business informationservices division, said the Dialog acquisition would complementexisting Knight-Ridder databases.   ``Dialog has been a pioneer in the electronic informationbusinesses and is an industry leader in terms of number ofcustomers, revenue, size, breadth and depth of database,'' Ray said.   The sale was expected to be completed in the third quarter.   Knight-Ridder is a national information and communicationscompany with operations that include broadcasting, publishing,cable television and information services.   Lockheed has received a number of inquiries about selling Dialogover the past year and a half, said spokesman Hud Englehart in thecompany's Calabasas, Calif., headquarters.   ``It's a matter of having a very interested buyer making a veryattractive offer,'' Englehart said, noting the sale price was 3{times Dialog's annual revenue.   In 1987, Dialog had a pretax profit of $17 million on revenue of$98.1 million.</TEXT></DOC>